<h1>Two sample inference</h1>




<h3>Two sample KS test</h3>

We have same set up as before. We want to test

<blockquote>
H<sub>0</sub>: F = G Vs H<sub>1</sub>: F 
                                         <img src=
                                         "resources/statinf2/neq.png"
                                         align=top>
                                         
                                          G
</blockquote>

or

<blockquote>
H<sub>0</sub>: F = G Vs H<sub>1</sub>: F 
                                         <img src=
                                         "resources/statinf2/sgt.png"
                                         align=top>
                                         
                                          G
</blockquote>

or

<blockquote>
H<sub>0</sub>: F = G Vs H<sub>1</sub>: F 
                                         <img src=
                                         "resources/statinf2/slt.png"
                                         align=top>
                                         
                                          G
</blockquote>

Let F<sub>m</sub> and G<sub>n</sub> denote the empirical distributions of
the X's and the Y's , respectively. 
Define

<blockquote>

D = sup<sub>x</sub> |
F<sub>m</sub>(x)-G<sub>n</sub>(x) |<br>

D<sub>+</sub> = sup<sub>x</sub> 
(F<sub>m</sub>(x)-G<sub>n</sub>(x))<br>

D = sup<sub>x</sub> 
(G<sub>n</sub>(x)-F<sub>m</sub>(x))

</blockquote>

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise 2KS.1:</font></b> 
   
   Show that 
   
   <blockquote>
   D<sub>+</sub> = 
   max{0, max<sub>i</sub>(i/m - 
   G<sub>n</sub>(X<sub>(i)</sub>))}
   </blockquote>
   
   Here X<sub>(i)</sub> is the i-th order statistic of the X's.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise 2KS.2:</font></b> 
   
   State and prove a similar result for D<sub>-</sub>
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise 2KS.3:</font></b> 
   
   Show that 
   
   <blockquote>
   D = max{ D<sub>-</sub>, D<sub>+</sub>}
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise 2KS.4:</font></b> 
   
   We want want to reject H<sub>0</sub> for large values of the test
   statistic. Which test statistic should we use for which H<sub>1</sub>?
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

The actual distributions of D, D<sub>-</sub>and D<sub>+</sub> are
complicated. Here are the asymptotic distributions under H<sub>0</sub>.
<p>

<table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
<b>Theorem:</b>

As min(m,n) 
            <img src=
            "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
            align=middle>
            
             
             <img src=
             "resources/statinf2/inf.png"
             align=top>
             
             , 

<blockquote>
P(sqrt(mn/(m+n)) D 
                   <img src=
                   "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                   align=top>
                   
                    x) 
                       <img src=
                       "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
                       align=middle>
                       
                        H(x),
under H<sub>0</sub>,
</blockquote>

where

<blockquote>


<table border=0>


<tr>
<td align=right>
H(x) = 
</td>
<td>
 1- 2 
      <img src=
      "resources/statinf2/sum.gif"
      align=middle>
      
      <sub>j</sub> (-1)<sup>j-1</sup>
exp(-2j<sup>2</sup> x<sup>2</sup>)
</td>
<td align=left>
 if x 
      <img src=
      "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
      align=top>
      
        0
</td>
</tr>


<tr>
<td align=right>

</td>
<td>
0
</td>
<td align=left>
else
</td>
</tr>


</table>


</blockquote>


</td></tr></table>


<p>

<table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
<b>Theorem:</b>

As min(m,n) 
            <img src=
            "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
            align=middle>
            
             
             <img src=
             "resources/statinf2/inf.png"
             align=top>
             
             , 

<blockquote>
P(sqrt(mn/(m+n)) D<sub>+</sub> 
                               <img src=
                               "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                               align=top>
                               
                                x)
 
 <img src=
 "resources/statinf2/rarrow.png"
 align=middle>
 
  H(x), under H<sub>0</sub>,
</blockquote>

where

<blockquote>


<table border=0>


<tr>
<td align=right>
H(x) = 
</td>
<td>
 1- exp(-2x<sup>2</sup>)
</td>
<td align=left>
 if x 
      <img src=
      "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
      align=top>
      
        0
</td>
</tr>


<tr>
<td align=right>

</td>
<td>
0
</td>
<td align=left>
else
</td>
</tr>


</table>


</blockquote>

The very same limit works for D<sub>-</sub> as well.

</td></tr></table>





